Some rare Alpina BMW E30 builds stand out not just for their performance, but for unusual custom details like full glass panoramic roofs. These roof conversions were never standard and instantly make the cars visually unique.

Models such as the Alpina C2 2.7 and B3 2.7 were hand built, high performance versions of the E30, officially registered as Alpina vehicles in Germany. Compared to a standard 325i, they received extensive engine, suspension, and interior upgrades, with the B3 2.7 producing around 201hp and reaching roughly 141mph (227km/h).

Already rare collector cars, a small number have been taken even further by enthusiasts fitting custom glass or polycarbonate panoramic roofs. These werenât factory options from BMW or Alpina, but theyâve turned the cars into striking one off showpieces.

The BMW Sauber V8-era Formula 1 carsâmost notably the F1.06, F1.07, F1.08, and F1.09âmarked a significant chapter in BMWâs return as a full works team. Introduced in 2006, the F1.06 represented BMWâs transition from engine supplier to complete constructor after taking over Sauber. With the new FIA regulations mandating a switch from V10s to 2.4-liter V8s, BMW debuted the P86, a compact, high-revving engine that showcased the brandâs engineering precision. The car immediately impressed with its stability, reliability, and efficient aerodynamics, setting the foundation for BMWâs rapid rise in the championship standings.

The evolution continued with the F1.07 and F1.08, each iteration becoming more refined and competitive. The P86/7 V8 engine matured into one of the strongest power units on the grid, known for its responsiveness and durability, allowing BMW Sauber to consistently score points. The pinnacle of the V8 era for BMW came in 2008 with the F1.08, a car capable of challenging the top teams. This led to the teamâs lone Formula 1 victory at the 2008 Canadian Grand Prix with Robert Kubicaâan achievement that symbolized how far the program had come in just a few seasons.

However, the momentum slowed with the introduction of KERS and shifting regulations in 2009. The F1.09 struggled to keep pace with rapidly advancing competitors, and the global financial crisis pressured BMW to withdraw from Formula 1 at the end of that season. Despite this abrupt ending, the V8-era BMW Sauber cars remain remembered for their technical excellence, clean GermanâSwiss engineering philosophy, and their ability to transform a midfield team into a genuine contender in a remarkably short time.

A hand throttle works by manually controlling the engineâs airflow or fuel input, just like pressing the gas pedal but using your hand instead of your foot. In most cars, the throttle is connected to the engine through a cable or electronic sensor. When the pedal is pressed, it opens the throttle plate, letting in more air and fuel to increase engine speed.

When the main cable or pedal mechanism fails, drivers can sometimes rig a temporary hand throttle by pulling that same cable directly with their hand or attaching a lever to control it. In rally emergencies, the co-driver might sit partially out the window and pull on a makeshift cable connected to the engineâs throttle linkage. By adjusting the tension, they could increase or decrease engine power, allowing the driver to keep steering, shifting, and braking normally while still moving the car.

Drifting isnât just sliding, itâs controlled chaos. Every drift is a balance between grip, throttle, and instinct. Hereâs what separates pros from tyre-burners ð

â 1ï¸â£ Weight Transfer:
The heart of drifting, shifting your carâs weight smoothly between corners keeps traction under control. Throw it too fast, and youâll spin. Too slow, and youâll straighten out. âï¸

â 2ï¸â£ Throttle Control:
The accelerator is your paintbrush. Feather it to maintain the slide, too much gas and youâll oversteer, too little and youâll lose the drift. ð¨

â 3ï¸â£ Counter Steering:
When the car slides, your steering wheel becomes your lifeline. Turn opposite to the slide to balance your rear end timing is everything. ð¹ï¸

â 4ï¸â£ Handbrake Technique:
Used to initiate or extend a drift, but the trick is to release smoothly so the tyres regain grip at the perfect moment. ð

â 5ï¸â£ Entry Speed:
Enter too slow, no angle. Enter too fast, you spin out. Learning the âsweet spotâ is where true drifters shine. ð

â 6ï¸â£ Tire Pressure & Grip:
Slightly lower pressure in the rear tyres makes them break traction faster â but too low and you lose control. Fine-tune based on surface and weather. âï¸

â 7ï¸â£ Line of Sight:
Look where you want to go, not where you are. The car always follows your eyes, this trick saves countless spins. ð

â 8ï¸â£ Suspension Setup:
A stiffer rear end and balanced camber keep your car predictable mid-slide, the right setup can make even a stock car feel like a drift machine. âï¸

Drifting isnât about fighting the car â itâs about dancing with it. Once you sync throttle, steering, and instinct, thatâs when the smoke turns into art. ð¨ð¥

The Dachshund, also known as the "sausage dog," is a beloved breed famous for its unique body shape and lively personality. Originally bred in Germany to hunt badgers, this small but courageous dog features a long body and short legs, perfectly designed for digging into burrows and tracking prey. Today, while Dachshunds are more commonly kept as family pets, their hunting instincts remain strong. ð

There are three coat varietiesâsmooth, wire-haired, and long-hairedâand Dachshunds also come in two sizes: standard and miniature. Despite their small stature, Dachshunds have big personalities and are known for their bravery, independence, and loyalty. Their playful nature makes them a fun companion, though they can be a bit stubborn, requiring patience when it comes to training. ð¾

Dachshunds are highly energetic and require regular exercise to stay healthy. However, their long backs make them prone to spinal issues, particularly intervertebral disc disease (IVDD), so care must be taken to avoid activities that could strain their backs, like jumping or running on stairs. With proper care, these dogs can lead long, active lives, often staying energetic well into their senior years. ðª

Despite their challenges, Dachshunds are cherished for their affectionate and fun-loving personalities. They tend to form close bonds with their families, making them excellent companions. Their small size makes them adaptable to both city living and the countryside, and their playful yet alert nature ensures they remain a favorite breed worldwide. ð
